New data on red tide: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Flora and Wildlife Florida (FWC) shows a general reduction in the concentration of red tides in parts of Tampa Bay Bay.
According to the FWC, the conditions of heterogeneous algal bloom are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatea, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier ̶, which indicates a decrease in concentrations.
Red tide stretches about 130 miles along the coast from the northern part of Pinellas district to the southern part of Lee district.
The areas of flowering can be found about 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less places than last week.
Red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, midpoint concentrations were recorded in Pinellas County or the associated offshore area, low to high concentration in the offshore area of Hillsborough, common to high concentration in Manatea County, common to high concentration in the Sarasota County or associated offshore area, common to medium concentration in Charlotte County, common to high concentration in Lee County or the associated offshore area, and low concentration in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
